Pour the @water{200%ml} into a large #saucepan{} with a pinch of @salt{pinch}
and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @chopped kale{100%g} and @bulgur wheat{100%g}, bring back to the
boil, pop a #lid{} on and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve. Meanwhile line
a #baking tray{} with foil.

Zest the @lemon{1/2%lemon}(zested then cut into wedges) then chop into wedges.
Roughly chop the @dill{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). In a #mixing bowl{},
combine the lemon zest, @ground coriander{1%tsp} and half the dill with a
pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and a squeeze of lemon juice. Add the
@coley fillet{2} and use your hands to coat it in the mixture.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Transfer the coley to the prepared #baking tray{} and grill until cooked,
~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The coley is cooked when opaque in the centre.

Meanwhile, cut the @fennel{1} in half lengthways, remove the triangle root in
the middle, then thinly slice widthways.

In a large #bowl{}, mix the remaining dill with the @wholegrain mustard{1/2%tbsp},
@mayonnaise{1%tbsp} and @capers{15%g}. Add a squeeze of lemon juice. Add the
fennel and use your hands to thoroughly combine. Season to taste with @salt{}
and @pepper{}. Add more lemon juice if needed.

Fluff up the bulgur with a #fork{}. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}
if needed.

Divide the kale and bulgur between your plates and top with the grilled coley.
Serve the fennel remoulade alongside.